<BlogPost
  title="RSS Didn't Die — The Open Web Just Got Quiet"
  description="Everyone declared RSS dead when Google Reader shut down. It has been quietly powering newsletters, podcasts, and the fediverse the whole time."
  slug="rss-and-the-open-web-in-2026"
  tag="Open Web"
  date="2026-06-17"
>
  <p>
    The standard story is that RSS died in 2013 when Google Reader shut down. It&rsquo;s a tidy story, and
    it&rsquo;s wrong. RSS didn&rsquo;t die — it went infrastructural. It stopped being a product you opened
    and became plumbing you never see.
  </p>

  <h2>Where it actually went</h2>
  <p>Look at what runs on feeds today:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Every podcast.</strong> The entire podcast ecosystem is RSS. When you subscribe in any app,
      you&rsquo;re subscribing to a feed. A multi-billion-dollar medium quietly standardized on a format
      from 1999.</li>
    <li><strong>The fediverse.</strong> Mastodon and friends expose feeds, and the whole model — follow a
      source, get its updates in your own client — is the RSS idea wearing new clothes.</li>
    <li><strong>Newsletters.</strong> The newsletter boom is the reader-in-your-inbox pattern that RMail was
      doing here in 2005. Same need, different delivery.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why &ldquo;dead&rdquo; stuck anyway</h2>
  <p>
    RSS lost the thing that makes technologies <em>feel</em> alive: a consumer product with a logo. Google
    Reader was the face, and when the face went away, people assumed the body had too. But a feed is a
    boring, durable contract — &ldquo;here is my content as structured XML, poll it when you like&rdquo; — and
    boring durable contracts are exactly what survive.
  </p>
  <blockquote>The open web didn&rsquo;t lose. It just stopped advertising.</blockquote>

  <h2>Getting back into feeds</h2>
  <p>
    Starting again is easy. Pick a feed reader, then add the sources you actually want — a few blogs, a
    newsletter or two, a podcast. Most sites still publish a feed even when they don&rsquo;t advertise it, and
    readers can auto-discover it from a tag in the page. Within a week you have a calm, chronological stream of
    exactly the sources you chose and nothing else: no ranking, no &ldquo;suggested for you,&rdquo; no outrage
    bait engineered to keep you scrolling. It is the antidote to the feed you didn&rsquo;t pick.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it matters now</h2>
  <p>
    The case for feeds is stronger in 2026 than it was in 2013. The alternative — algorithmic timelines you
    don&rsquo;t control, content you can only reach inside one app — has shown its costs. A feed is a
    standing offer of <strong>portable, un-gatekept, chronological access</strong> to a source you chose.
    No ranking, no engagement farming, no lock-in. Subscribe, and the source comes to you on your terms.
  </p>
  <p>
    That&rsquo;s why KB Cafe keeps a <a href="/feeds">Feeds</a> section. Not nostalgia — a bet that the open
    web&rsquo;s quietest format is also one of its most resilient.
  </p>

